misconceptions.inferred_category_name: No detectable notional-machine misconception (solution matches Java execution model)
misconceptions.student_thought_process: The student believes that: (1) printing a prompt does not itself read input, so they must call nextDouble() to get numbers; (2) values entered by the user are stored in variables v0, v1, and t; (3) arithmetic on doubles behaves like the math formula; and (4) computing a once and printing it will show the result.
misconceptions.conceptual_gap: There isn’t an apparent gap here: the code reflects the correct Java mental model. The prompt is just output, input is read explicitly, variables don’t auto-update (and they aren’t expected to here), and division is done in floating point because the operands are doubles.
misconceptions.error_manifestation: No error; program should compile and produce correct output for valid numeric input (aside from the general edge case of t = 0, which would yield Infinity/-Infinity).
